Preheat the oven to 200 degrees and chop the @potatoes{450} into 2cm wide wedges (no
need to peel). Pop on a #baking tray{} and drizzle with @oil{some}. Season with
@salt{} and @pepper{}, toss to coat then spread out and roast on the top shelf
of your oven until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}, turning halfway.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and finely slice the @red onion{1}. Heat a drizzle of
@oil{some} in large #frying pan{} on medium heat and when hot, add the onion
and a pinch of @salt{} and @sugar{}. Lower the heat and cook, stirring
occasionally, until soft and caramelised, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Meanwhile, remove the @confit duck legs{2} from their packet and discard the
fat, skin and jelly. Use your hands to pull the meat from the bones and shred
it into small pieces. When the onions are soft, stir the shredded duck into
the #pan{} along with the @water{50}. Bring to the boil then lower the heat
and bubble until reduced, ~{6-8%minutes} - you want the water to have evaporated,
but for the duck to still be quite moist.

Meanwhile, grate the @mature cheddar cheese{60} and split open the
@brioche hot dog buns{2}. Put the buns on a baking tray and spread the
@Dijon mustard{1} evenly inside each one. Preheat your grill to high (move the
potatoes down to the bottom shelf if they are in the same oven).

Carefully spoon the duck confit mixture inside each bun, packing it in well.
Sprinkle the cheddar over each then pop under the grill until golden and
bubbling, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Divide the wedges between your plates then serve the 'duck dogs' alongside.
Finish with a handful of @wild rocket{40} on top of each and a dollop of
@mayonnaise{1} alongside for dipping your chips. Dig in!

> Our confit duck 'dog' is comfort food of the highest order. Think sweet
> brioche bun topped with shredded duck and bubbling cheddar cheese. Yes
> PLEASE.